commit.message:
[core] disable MPTCP support by default

Matthieu Baerts notes:
MPTCP is currently not compatible with KTLS: they both use the
same technique to extend TCP behaviour in the kernel (TCP ULP).

Disable network_mptcp if socket() IPPROTO_MPTCP fails and omit trace,
since it probably indicates MPTCP support is not available, and lighttpd
transparently falls back to IPPROTO_TCP.

Matthieu Baerts notes:
Creating a socket with IPPROTO_MPTCP may fail with
ENOPROTOOPT (Protocol not available: linked to net.mptcp.enabled sysctl)
EPROTONOSUPPORT (Protocol not supported: MPTCP not compiled on >= v5.6)
EINVAL (Invalid argument: MPTCP is not available on kernels < 5.6).

If socket() failed for other reasons, then the socket() IPPROTO_TCP
fallback which immediately follows will likely fail the same way and
lighttpd will error out.

  "[core] add MPTCP support"
  https://github.com/lighttpd/lighttpd1.4/pull/132

[core] add MPTCP support

Multipath TCP (MPTCP), standardized in RFC8684 [1], is a TCP extension
that enables a TCP connection to use different paths.
Multipath TCP has been used for several use cases.
On smartphones, Multipath TCP enables seamless handovers between
cellular and Wi-Fi networks while preserving established connections.
This use-case is what pushed Apple to use MPTCP since 2013 in multiple
applications [2]. On dual-stack hosts, Multipath TCP enables the TCP
connection to automatically use the best performing path,
either IPv4 or IPv6. If one path fails, Multipath TCP automatically
uses the other path. To benefit from MPTCP, both the client and the
server have to support it.

Multipath TCP is a backward-compatible TCP extension that is enabled by
default on recent Linux distributions (Debian, Ubuntu, Redhat, ...).
Multipath TCP is included in the Linux kernel since version 5.6 [3].
To use Multipath TCP on Linux, a server application must explicitly
enable it when creating the socket. No need to change anything else in
the application. This is what the attached patch is doing.

It is important to note that a MPTCP-enabled server continues to accept
regular TCP connections that do not use the Multipath TCP extension
without any performance impact.

When a connection request is received, and is linked to a listening
socket with MPTCP support, the kernel will simply check if MPTCP
options are present. If not, the accepted socket will be a "plain" TCP
one.

This commit modifies the creation of sockets on Linux, trying to use
Multipath TCP is available. If not, a plain TCP socket is created
instead. A new option is now available: `server.network-mptcp`. This
option is enabled by default. It seems important to enable this option
by default on the server side, to let clients using MPTCP while not
degrading performances when "plain" TCP is used. If the option is not
enabled by default, it looks difficult to convince each administrator to
enable it explicitly. This technology is mainly useful for the client
side while it doesn't change much for the server side where no other
configuration is needed.

Link: https://www.rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc8684.html [1]
Link: https://www.tessares.net/apples-mptcp-story-so-far/ [2]
Link: https://www.mptcp.dev [3]

[core] add default to builtin mimetype.assign

add default "application/octet-stream" to builtin mimetype.assign

If mimetype.assign is not specified in lighttpd.conf, the builtin
default for mimetype.assign is used.  This change adds a default
  "" => "application/octet-stream"
to the builtin mimetype.assign.  The effect is that ETag and
Last-Modified are sent for static files which use this default,
where previously ETag and Last-Modified were omitted for static
files without a specified Content-Type.  This aligns with widely used
behavior in distro packages of lighttpd, which specify mimetype.assign
to include "" => "application/octet-stream"

The historical reason for omitting ETag and Last-Modified for static
files with unspecified Content-Type was to avoid first-time user
misconfiguration of lighttpd.conf, resulting in download of files
intended to be executed by CGI (e.g. .php, .pl, .py), and then
over-aggressive caching by browsers even after the misconfiguration
was corrected.  The over-agressive caching by browsers in this case
seems to be less of an issue today than it was, and many distro packages
additionally include lighttpd.conf protection against downloading code,
  e.g. static-file.exclude-extensions = ( ".php", ".pl", ".py" )

[mod_openssl] use internal asn1_time fn on 32-bit (fixes #3244)

(thx Tobias Jakobi (Compleo))

use internal asn1_time conversion function on 32-bit builds in order to
test if a certificate is active (valid time in range notBefore and
notAfter from the certificate)

lighttpd sets _TIME_BITS=64 to build with 64-bit time_t (supported with
glibc 2.34 and later) but there can a mismatch if lighttpd uses 64-bit
time_t and underlying libraries (built on 32-bit systems) such as
openssl use 32-bit time_t *and* expose API functions using time_t.

This issue occurs in lighttpd mod_openssl use of ASN1_TIME_cmp_time_t().
This patch implements a workaround to use an internal implementation to
parse asn1_time on 32-bit systems, which might use 32-bit time_t.

(An alternative approach would be to test openssl during the build to
determine bitness of time_t used in openssl, but that would be much more
work and has diminishing returns since modern and maintained 32-bit OS
distros have migrated or are migrating to 64-bit time_t, and 64-bit OS
distros already use 64-bit time_t.)

[TLS] default to stronger ciphers w/ PFS and AEAD

(behavior change; previously announced)

TLS default ciphers are now (equivalent to)
  openssl ciphers 'EECDH+AESGCM:CHACHA20:!PSK:!DHE'
ciphers are forward-secret and support authenticated encryption (AEAD)

Little or no impact is expected for lighttpd configs already using lighttpd TLS defaults
(and supported clients, i.e. those which have not already reached end-of-life).

x-ref:
https://developers.cloudflare.com/ssl/reference/cipher-suites/recommendations/

[mod_redirect] url.redirect-code = 308 new default

(behavior change; previously announced)

url.redirect-code = 308 new default for >= HTTP/1.1 and not HEAD or GET
(301 is still default sent to HTTP/1.0 and to all HEAD and GET methods)

New default takes effect only if lighttpd.conf does not contain an
explicit setting for url.redirect-code, which continues to be honored.
